</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH=12>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING:0PX; FONT-SIZE:9PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH=48>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING:0PX; FONT-SIZE:9PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(a)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Net summer rated capacity is determined by annual testing and may vary from year to year due to, among other things, the operating and physical conditions of the units.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(b)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Baseload generation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(c)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	MGE's share. See &quot;Columbia&quot; below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(d)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Facility is jointly owned. Based on the terms of the joint plant agreement between MGE and the UW, the UW has the ability to reduce net capability of these units by approximately 17&nbsp;MW in the summer. The net summer rated capacity shown reflects this decrease. See &quot;WCCF&quot; below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(e)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	MGE's share. See &quot;Elm Road&quot; below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(f)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Three facilities are owned by MGE, and three facilities are leased.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(g)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	These facilities are owned by MGE.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(h)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Nameplate capacity rating is 11&nbsp;MW.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(i)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Nameplate capacity rating is 30&nbsp;MW.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<I>
	Columbia
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE and two other utilities jointly own Columbia, a coal-fired generating facility consisting of two 512&nbsp;MW units, which, at December&nbsp;31, 2016, accounts for 30% of MGE's net summer rated capacity. Power from this facility is shared in proportion to each owner's ownership interest. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE had a 22% ownership interest in Columbia. The other owners are WPL, which operates Columbia, and WPSC. The Columbia units burn low-sulfur coal obtained from the Powder River Basin coal fields located in Wyoming. The coal inventory supply for the Columbia units decreased from approximately 88 days on December&nbsp;31, 2015, to approximately 65 days on December&nbsp;31, 2016. See &quot;Executive Overview&quot; under Item&nbsp;7. Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations, for a discussion of the reduction in MGE's ownership share in Columbia commencing January&nbsp;2017 and continuing through June&nbsp;2020.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	20
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage21"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
<I>
	Elm Road Units
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE Power Elm Road and two other owners own undivided interests in the Elm Road Units, consisting of two 615&nbsp;MW units, which, at December&nbsp;31, 2016, account for 14% of MGE's net summer rated capacity. Power from these units is shared in proportion to each owner's ownership interest. MGE Power Elm Road owns an 8.33% ownership interest in the Elm Road Units, and its interest in the Elm Road Units&nbsp;is leased to MGE. The other owners are Wisconsin Energy Corporation, which operates the Units, and WPPI Energy, Inc. The Elm Road Units&nbsp;burn bituminous coal obtained from northern West Virginia and southwestern Pennsylvania, and Powder River Basin coal from Wyoming. MGE's share of the coal inventory supply for the Elm Road Units&nbsp;increased from approximately 50 days on December&nbsp;31, 2015, to approximately 51 days on December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE leases MGE Power Elm Road's ownership interest in the Elm Road Units&nbsp;pursuant to two separate facility leases. The financial terms of each facility lease include a capital structure of 55% equity and 45% long-term debt, return on equity of 12.7%, and a lease term of 30 years. At the end of the respective lease terms, MGE may, at its option, renew the facility lease for an additional term, purchase the leased ownership interest at fair market value, or allow the lease to end. The Unit&nbsp;1 and Unit&nbsp;2 leases commenced with the commercial operation of each respective unit.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<I>
	WCCF
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE Power West Campus and the UW jointly own undivided interests in a natural gas-fired cogeneration facility on the UW campus. The facility has the capacity to produce 20,000 tons of chilled water, 500,000 pounds per hour of steam, and approximately 150&nbsp;MW of electricity. The UW owns 45% of the facility, which represents its interest in the chilled-water and steam assets. These assets are used to meet a part of the UW's need for air-conditioning and steam-heat capacity. MGE Power West Campus owns 55% of the facility, which represents its interest in the electric generating assets. These assets are used to provide electricity to MGE's customers. The UW's share of the plant and portion of the earnings from the WCCF are not reflected in the consolidated financial statements of MGE&nbsp;Energy or MGE. MGE Power West Campus' share of the plant is reflected in property, plant, and equipment on MGE&nbsp;Energy's and MGE's consolidated balance sheets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE leases the electric generating assets owned by MGE Power West Campus and is responsible for operating the entire facility. The financial terms of the facility lease include a capital structure of 53% equity and 47% long-term debt, return on equity of 12.1%, and a lease term of 30 years. At the end of the lease term in 2035, MGE may, at its option, renew the facility lease for an additional term, purchase the generating facility at fair market value, or allow the lease contract to end.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Electric and Gas Distribution Facilities
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE owned 872 miles of overhead electric distribution line and 1,236 miles of underground electric distribution cable, all of which are located in Wisconsin. These electric distribution facilities are connected by approximately 52 substations, installed with a capacity of 1,190,500 kVA. MGE's gas facilities include 2,765 miles of distribution mains, which are all owned by MGE.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	A significant portion of MGE's electric and gas distribution facilities are located above or underneath highways, streets, other public places or property that others own. MGE believes that it has satisfactory rights to use those places or property in the form of permits, grants, easements, and licenses; however, it has not necessarily undertaken to examine the underlying title to the land upon which the rights rest.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Encumbrances
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	The principal plants and properties of MGE are subject to the lien of its Indenture of Mortgage and Deed of Trust dated as of January&nbsp;1, 1946, as amended and supplemented, under which MGE's first mortgage bonds are issued. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, there were $1.2&nbsp;million of first mortgage bonds outstanding. See Footnote&nbsp;9 of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for additional information regarding MGE's first mortgage bonds.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE Power Elm Road has collaterally assigned its right to lease payments from MGE for the Elm Road Units&nbsp;in order to secure the repayment of $62.6&nbsp;million of senior secured notes issued by MGE Power Elm Road. See Footnote&nbsp;9 of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for additional information regarding these senior notes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

	See discussion below as well as &quot;Liquidity and Capital Resources - Financing Activities&quot; under Item&nbsp;7. Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations, for a description of restrictions applicable to dividend payments by MGE.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Dividend Restrictions
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Dividend payments by MGE to MGE&nbsp;Energy are subject to restrictions arising under a PSCW rate order and, to a lesser degree, MGE's first mortgage bonds. The PSCW order restricts any dividends, above the PSCW authorized amount of $43&nbsp;million, that MGE may pay MGE&nbsp;Energy if its common equity ratio, calculated in the manner used in the rate proceeding, is less than 55%. MGE's thirteen month rolling average common equity ratio at December&nbsp;31, 2016, is 60.2%, as determined under the calculation used in the rate proceeding. This restriction did not impact
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	23
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage24"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
	MGE's payment of dividends in 2016. Cash dividends of $50.0&nbsp;million and $30.0&nbsp;million were paid by MGE to MGE&nbsp;Energy in 2016 and 2015, respectively. In 2016, MGE also transferred its ownership interest in MGE Transco to MGE&nbsp;Energy in the form of a dividend in kind of $15.8&nbsp;million. The rate proceeding calculation includes as indebtedness imputed amounts for MGE's outstanding purchase power capacity payments and other PSCW adjustments, but does not include the indebtedness associated with MGE Power Elm Road and MGE Power West Campus, which are consolidated into MGE's financial statements but are not direct obligations of MGE.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE has covenanted with the holders of its first mortgage bonds not to declare or pay any dividend or make any other distribution on or purchase any shares of its common stock unless, after giving effect thereto, the aggregate amount of all such dividends and distributions and all amounts applied to such purchases, after December&nbsp;31, 1945, shall not exceed the earned surplus (retained earnings) accumulated subsequent to December&nbsp;31, 1945. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, approximately $338.5&nbsp;million was available for the payment of dividends under this covenant.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Stock Split
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	On December&nbsp;20, 2013, MGE&nbsp;Energy's Board of Directors declared a three-for-two stock split of MGE&nbsp;Energy's outstanding shares of common stock, effective in the form of a stock dividend. Shareholders of record at the close of business on January&nbsp;24, 2014, received one additional share of MGE&nbsp;Energy common stock for every two shares of common stock owned on that date. The additional shares were distributed on February&nbsp;7, 2014. Shareholders received cash in lieu of any fractional shares of common stock they otherwise would have received in connection with the dividend. All share and per share data provided in this report give effect to this stock split.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:42PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	*
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:42PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Under the MGE&nbsp;Energy, Inc. Direct Stock Purchase and Dividend Reinvestment Plan (Stock Plan), common stock shares deliverable to plan participants may be either newly issued shares or shares purchased on the open market, as determined from time to time by MGE&nbsp;Energy. MGE&nbsp;Energy uses open market purchases to provide shares to meet obligations to participants in the Stock Plan. The shares are purchased on the open market through a securities broker-dealer and then are reissued under the Stock Plan as needed to meet share delivery requirements. The volume and timing of share repurchases in the open market depends upon the level of dividend reinvestment and optional share purchases being made from time to time by plan participants. As a result, there is no specified maximum number of shares to be repurchased and no specified termination date for the repurchases. All shares issued through the Stock Plan, whether newly issued or reissued following open market purchases, are issued and sold by MGE&nbsp;Energy pursuant to a registration statement that was filed with the SEC and is currently effective.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	MGE
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	None.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM__TOC475524569">

<EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT">
<B>
	Item&nbsp;7. Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT">
<B>
<I>
	General
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy is an investor-owned public utility holding company operating through subsidiaries in five business segments:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Regulated electric utility operations, conducted through MGE,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Regulated gas utility operations, conducted through MGE,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Nonregulated energy operations, conducted through MGE Power and its subsidiaries,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Transmission investments, representing our equity investment in ATC and ATC Holdco, and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	All other, which includes corporate operations and services.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Our principal subsidiary is MGE, which generates and distributes electric energy, distributes natural gas, and represents a majority portion of our assets, liabilities, revenues, and expenses. MGE generates and distributes electricity to approximately 149,000 customers in Dane County, Wisconsin, including the city of Madison, and purchases and distributes natural gas to approximately 154,000 customers in the Wisconsin counties of Columbia, Crawford, Dane, Iowa, Juneau, Monroe, and Vernon.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Our nonregulated energy operations own interests in electric generating capacity that is leased to MGE. The ownership/leasing structure was adopted under applicable state regulatory guidelines for MGE's participation in these generation facilities, consisting principally of a stable return on the equity investment in the new generation facilities over the term of the related leases. The nonregulated energy operations include an ownership interest in two coal-fired generating units in Oak Creek, Wisconsin and a partial ownership of a cogeneration project on the UW-Madison campus. A third party operates the units in Oak Creek, and MGE operates the cogeneration project. Due to the nature of MGE's participation in these facilities, the results of our nonregulated operations are also consolidated into MGE's consolidated financial position and results of operations under applicable accounting standards.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT">
<B>
<I>
	Executive Overview
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Our primary focus today and for the foreseeable future is our core utility customers at MGE as well as creating long-term value for our shareholders. MGE continues to face the challenge of providing its customers with reliable power at competitive prices. MGE meets this challenge by investing in more efficient generation projects, including renewable energy sources. MGE will continue to focus on growing earnings while controlling operating and fuel costs. MGE maintains safe and efficient operations in addition to providing customer value. We believe it is critical to maintain a strong credit standing consistent with financial strength in MGE as well as the parent company in order to accomplish these goals.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	We earn our revenue and generate cash from operations by providing electric and natural gas utility services, including electric power generation and electric power and gas distribution. The earnings and cash flows from the utility business are sensitive to various external factors, including:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Weather, and its impact on customer sales,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Economic conditions, including current business activity and employment and their impact on customer demand,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Regulation and regulatory issues, and their impact on the timing and recovery of costs,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Energy commodity prices, including natural gas prices,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Equity price risk pertaining to pension related assets,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Credit market conditions, including interest rates and our debt credit rating,
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Environmental laws and regulations, including adopted and pending environmental rule changes, and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Other factors listed in Item&nbsp;1A. Risk Factors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE&nbsp;Energy's earnings were $75.6&nbsp;million or $2.18 per share compared to $71.3&nbsp;million or $2.06 per share for the same period in the prior year. MGE's earnings for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, were $51.2&nbsp;million compared to $45.4&nbsp;million for the same period in the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">

</TR>

<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>

	27
</P>
</TD>

<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Our net income during 2016 compared to 2015 primarily reflects the effects of the following factors:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Electric net income increased due to a 5.4% increase in residential electric retail sales as the result of more favorable weather conditions in 2016 compared to 2015. Electric utility operations experienced an increase in operating and maintenance costs partially offsetting the increase in net income compared to the same period in the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Carrying costs incurred during construction of the Elm Road Units&nbsp;and WCCF were recognized by MGE Power Elm Road and MGE Power West Campus over the period allowed for recovery in rates. The recovery period ended in 2015, contributing to a reduction in nonregulated earnings in 2016. The reduction in earnings was partially offset by an increase in lease revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Transmission investment income reflects our share of ATC's earnings. ATC's earnings for 2015 reflected a charge representing its estimate of its refund liability covering 2015, 2014, and a portion of 2013 associated with the return on equity complaint filed with FERC. See &quot;Other Matters&quot; below for additional information concerning ATC.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Our net income during 2015 compared to 2014 primarily reflects the effects of the following factors:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Electric net income decreased due to lower AFUDC and higher depreciation expense primarily related to the Columbia environmental project being placed in service in April&nbsp;(Unit&nbsp;2) and July&nbsp;2014 (Unit&nbsp;1). In addition, there was a 0.3% decrease in electric retail sales in 2015 compared to 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Gas net income decreased due to a 27.0% decrease in gas retail sales reflecting lower customer demand compared to the demand resulting from the extremely cold weather experienced in 2014. Heating degree days (a measure for determining the impact of weather during the heating season) decreased by 18.9% compared to 2014. The average temperature in January&nbsp;2015 was 20.1 degrees compared to 11.5 degrees in 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	ATC's earnings for 2015 reflected a charge representing its estimate of its refund liability covering 2015, 2014, and a portion of 2013 associated with the return on equity complaint filed with FERC. See &quot;Other Matters&quot; below for additional information concerning ATC.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	The increase in all other income primarily results from a decrease in voluntary contributions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	During 2016, the following events occurred:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	2016 Rates: In July&nbsp;2015, the PSCW approved MGE's request to extend the current accounting treatment for transmission related costs through 2016, conditioned upon MGE not filing a base rate case for 2016. This accounting treatment allows MGE to reflect any differential between transmission costs reflected in rates and actual costs incurred in its next rate case filing.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	2016 Annual Fuel Proceeding: In August&nbsp;2015, the PSCW approved a $0.00256/kWh fuel credit that began on September&nbsp;1, 2015, and continued throughout 2016. The fuel credit established a mechanism to return $10.9&nbsp;million of fuel savings to electric customers as a bill credit. MGE returned $8.3&nbsp;million of electric fuel-related savings to customers through bill credits during the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	In January&nbsp;2016, the PSCW lowered MGE's 2016 fuel rules monitored costs by $14.8&nbsp;million as a result of continued lower projected fuel costs in 2016. Also, in March&nbsp;2016, MGE filed its 2015 fuel plan reconciliation application showing an overcollection of 2015 fuel rules monitored costs. In July&nbsp;2016, the PSCW issued a final
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	28
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage29"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
	order stating that MGE shall refund the additional fuel savings incurred during 2015 and 2016 for a total of $15.7&nbsp;million to its retail electric customers over a one-month period. In September&nbsp;2016, MGE returned $15.5&nbsp;million to customers through bill credits.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE has deferred $5.6&nbsp;million of 2016 fuel savings that were in excess of the fuel savings included within the fuel credits referenced above. These costs will be subject to the PSCW's annual review of 2016 fuel costs, expected to be completed in 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Loss of Industrial Customer: In November&nbsp;2015, a large industrial customer announced its intention to relocate its operations out of state and to close its manufacturing facilities within our service territory. That closure is expected to occur in early 2017. For the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, this customer contributed approximately $3.4&nbsp;million and $3.8&nbsp;million, respectively, of pre-tax earnings. Our rate case filing for 2017 addressed the effects of the closure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	ATC Return on Equity: Several parties have filed complaints with the FERC seeking to reduce the base return on equity (ROE) used by MISO transmission owners, including ATC. In June&nbsp;2016, an administrative law judge issued an initial decision regarding a second filed complaint for the period February&nbsp;2015 through May&nbsp;2015 that would reduce the transmission owners' base ROE to 9.7%. ATC recorded an estimated refund liability with respect to the administrative law judge's order, which was reflected within our share of ATC earnings. On September&nbsp;28, 2016, FERC issued an order on the first complaint, for the period November&nbsp;2013 through February&nbsp;2015, reducing the base ROE to 10.32%. This base ROE also became effective September&nbsp;28, 2016, and will apply to future periods until FERC rules in the second complaint, at which time the base ROE ordered by FERC in the second complaint will prospectively become the authorized base ROE. See &quot;Other Matters&quot; below for additional information concerning ATC.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	During 2017, several items may affect us, including:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	2017 Rate Case Filing: On December&nbsp;15, 2016, the PSCW authorized MGE to decrease 2017 rates for retail electric customers by 0.8% or $3.3&nbsp;million and to increase rates for retail gas customers by 1.9% or $3.1&nbsp;million. The decrease in retail electric rates reflects declining fuel and purchased power costs. The increase in retail gas rates covers costs associated with MGE's natural gas system infrastructure improvements. The authorized return on common stock equity for 2017 is 9.8% on 57.2% common equity. The PSCW also approved MGE's request to extend the current accounting treatment for transmission related costs through 2018.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	ATC Return on Equity: Several parties have filed complaints with the FERC seeking to reduce the ROE used by MISO transmission owners, including ATC. Any change to ATC's ROE could result in lower equity earnings and distributions from ATC in the future. We derived approximately 6.8% and 6.4% of our net income for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, respectively, from our investment in ATC. See &quot;Other Matters&quot; below for additional information concerning ATC.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Environmental Initiatives: There are proposed legislation, rules, and initiatives involving matters related to air emissions, water effluent, hazardous materials, and greenhouse gases, all of which affect generation plant capital expenditures and operating costs as well as future operational planning. At present, it is unclear how the changes in the Presidential and EPA administration may affect pending or new legislative or rulemaking proposals or regulatory initiatives. Such legislation and rulemaking could significantly affect the costs of owning and operating fossil-fueled generating plants, such as Columbia and the Elm Road Units, from which we derive approximately 43% of our electric generating capacity as of December&nbsp;31, 2016. We would expect to seek and receive recovery of any such costs in rates; however, it is difficult to estimate the amount of such costs due to the uncertainty as to the timing and form of the legislation and rules, and the scope and time of the recovery of costs in rates, which may lag the incurrence of those costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	EPA's Clean Power Plan: In October&nbsp;2015, the EPA finalized its Clean Power Plan (CPP) rule with an effective date of December&nbsp;2015, setting guidelines and approval criteria for states to use in developing plans to control GHG emissions from existing fossil fuel-fired electric generating units (EGUs) and systems. Implementation of the rule is expected to have a direct impact on existing coal and natural gas fired generating units, including possible changes in dispatch and additional operating costs. Given the pending legal proceedings, the nature and timing of any final requirements is subject to uncertainty. If the rule remains substantially in its present form, it is expected to have a material impact on MGE.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	29
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage30"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
	Future Generation: During the first quarter of 2016, MGE entered into an agreement with WPL under which MGE may acquire up to 50&nbsp;MW of capacity in a gas-fired generating plant to be constructed by WPL at its Riverside Energy Center in Beloit, Wisconsin, during the five-year period following the in-service date of the plant. The plant is expected to be completed by early 2020. MGE and WPL have negotiated an amendment to the existing Columbia joint operating agreement, effective January&nbsp;1, 2017, under which MGE will reduce its obligation to pay certain capital expenditures (other than SCR-related expenditures) at Columbia prior to the expected in-service date of the Riverside gas-fired generating plant in exchange for a proportional reduction in MGE's ownership in Columbia. On January&nbsp;1 of each year, beginning in 2017 and ending June&nbsp;1, 2020, the ownership percentage will be adjusted, through a partial sale, based on the amount of capital expenditures foregone. During 2016, MGE accrued $14.8&nbsp;million of 2016 capital expenditures that MGE has forgone as part of the ownership transfer agreement with WPL. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE classified $14.8&nbsp;million of Columbia assets as held-for-sale on the consolidated balance sheets. In January&nbsp;2017, MGE reduced its ownership interest in Columbia from 22.0% to 20.4% through the partial sale of plant assets to WPL. By June&nbsp;2020, MGE's ownership in Columbia is forecasted to be approximately 19%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Saratoga Wind Farm: On February&nbsp;21, 2017, MGE filed with the PSCW a letter notifying the commission of MGE's intent to seek approval to construct, own and operate a 66MW wind farm, consisting of 33 turbines, located near Saratoga, Iowa. MGE anticipates filing its formal application with the PSCW in March. If approved, construction of the project is expected to begin in early 2018, with an estimated capital cost of $107&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Financing Plans: In January&nbsp;2017, MGE issued $40&nbsp;million of new long-term unsecured debt carrying an interest rate of 3.76% per annum over its 35-year term. The proceeds of this debt financing were used to refinance the maturing $30&nbsp;million medium-term notes and, assist with the financing of additional capital expenditures. The covenants of this debt are substantially consistent with MGE's existing unsecured long-term debt. In accordance with applicable accounting guidance, MGE has classified the $30&nbsp;million of maturing medium-term notes as long-term debt on the consolidated balance sheets for 2016. MGE also plans to issue an additional $30&nbsp;million of new long-term debt during 2017 to cover capital expenditures and other corporate obligations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	The following discussion is based on the business segments as discussed in Footnote&nbsp;20 of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX">
	In July&nbsp;2015, the PSCW authorized MGE to freeze 2016 rates at 2015 levels for retail electric customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Deferral of fuel savings/fuel credit.
</I>
	During 2016, customers received a fuel credit on their bill related to the fuel savings of $21.1&nbsp;million, which decreased electric revenues when compared to 2015. This amount was partially offset by the 2016 deferred fuel rules monitored costs. In January&nbsp;2016, the PSCW lowered MGE's 2016 fuel rules monitored costs as a result of continued lower projected fuel costs in 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Volume
</I>
	. During 2016, there was a 5.4% increase in total residential sales volumes compared to the same period in the prior year driven by increased customer demand due, at least in part, to more favorable weather conditions, as evidenced by the higher number of cooling degree days.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-7.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Adjustments to Revenue
</I>
	. The adjustments to revenues amount includes the elimination of carrying costs for the Elm Road Units&nbsp;and the WCCF that were collected in electric rates ending in 2015, which were recognized as operating revenues in our Nonregulated Energy Operations segment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-7.667PX">
	MGE leases electric generating capacity from MGE Power Elm Road. MGE collects in rates the lease payments associated with the electric generating capacity as authorized by the PSCW. Any differential between estimated lease payments collected in rates and actual lease payments paid to MGE Power Elm Road are included in adjustments to revenues.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Sales to the market.
</I>
	Sales to the market represent wholesale sales made to third parties who are not ultimate users of the electricity. These sales may include spot market transactions on the markets operated by MISO. These sales may also include bilateral sales to other utilities or power marketers. Generating units are dispatched by MISO based on cost considerations as well as reliability of the system. Sales to the market typically occur when MGE has more generation and purchases online than are needed for its own system demand. The excess electricity is then sold to others in the market. For 2016, market volumes increased compared to the same period in the prior year, reflecting increased opportunities for sales, and those sales were made at higher market prices. The revenue generated from these sales is included in fuel rules monitored costs. See fuel rules discussion in Footnote&nbsp;16.b. of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Other
</I>
	. During 2016, other items affecting electric operating revenues increased $2.4&nbsp;million. MGE experienced an increase in residential and small commercial customers contributing to the increase in other electric revenue. Higher monthly on-peak sales also attributed to the increase.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Electric fuel and purchased power
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Electric fuel and purchased power costs reflect an increase in internal generation volumes partially offset by a decrease in the volume of purchased power when compared to the prior year. Adjustments related to the regulatory recovery for fuel costs, known as fuel rules, decreased purchased power expense. These items are explained below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	The decrease in expense (before fuel rules adjustments) reflects a 21.1% decrease in the volume of power purchased from third parties primarily as a result of the increased internal generation, partially offset by a 5.2% increase in the per-unit cost of purchased power.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Under fuel rules, MGE is required to defer electric fuel-related costs that fall outside a 2% cost tolerance band around the amount used in the most recent rate proceeding. Any fuel rules adjustments are reflected in purchased power expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For 2016, increased customer accounts costs are primarily related to higher customer billing expenses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Electric depreciation expense
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Electric depreciation expense decreased $0.8&nbsp;million for 2016, compared to the prior year. A new depreciation study approved by the PSCW, effective January&nbsp;1, 2016, resulted in a decrease in expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:6PX; WIDTH:30PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:30PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-7.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Rate/PGA changes
</I>
	. MGE recovers the cost of natural gas in its gas segment through the purchased gas adjustment clause (PGA). Under the PGA, MGE is able to pass through to its gas customers the cost of gas. Changes in PGA recoveries affect revenues but do not impact net income.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:30PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-7.667PX">
	The average retail rate per therm for 2016, decreased 5.0% compared to 2015, reflecting a $6.3&nbsp;million decrease in natural gas commodity costs (recovered through the PGA), partially offset by an increase in fixed rate charges.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-SIZE:12PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#8226;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Volume
</I>
	. For 2016, retail gas deliveries decreased 1.7% compared to the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Cost of gas sold
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For 2016, cost of gas sold decreased by $9.3&nbsp;million, compared to the prior year. The cost per therm of natural gas decreased 10.3%, which resulted in $7.6&nbsp;million of decreased expense. The volume of gas purchased decreased 2.2%, which resulted in $1.7&nbsp;million of decreased expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Gas operating and maintenance expenses
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Gas operating and maintenance expenses increased $1.0&nbsp;million for 2016 compared to 2015. The following changes contributed to the net change.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For 2016, increased customer accounts costs are due to higher customer billing expenses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Gas depreciation expense
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Gas depreciation expense increased $1.4&nbsp;million for 2016, compared to the prior year. This increase is primarily driven by an increase in gas utility plant in-service in 2016 and a new depreciation study approved by the PSCW, effective January&nbsp;1, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Nonregulated Energy Operations - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For 2016 and 2015, net income at the nonregulated energy operations segment was $19.1&nbsp;million and $20.1&nbsp;million, respectively. The nonregulated energy operations are conducted through MGE&nbsp;Energy's subsidiaries: MGE Power Elm Road (the Elm Road Units) and MGE Power West Campus (WCCF), which have been formed to own and lease electric generating capacity to assist MGE. Carrying costs incurred during construction of the Elm Road Units&nbsp;and WCCF were recognized by MGE Power Elm Road and MGE Power West Campus over the period allowed for recovery in rates. The recovery period ended in 2015, contributing to a reduction in nonregulated earnings in 2016. The reduction in earnings was partially offset by an increase in lease revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Transmission Investment Operations - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Transmission investment other income
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For 2016 and 2015, other income at the transmission investment segment was $8.4&nbsp;million and $7.7&nbsp;million, respectively. The transmission investment segment holds our interest in ATC and ATC Holdco, and its income reflects our equity in the earnings of ATC. ATC Holdco was formed in 2016. In the near term, it is expected that ATC Holdco will be pursuing transmission development opportunities that typically have long development and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Consolidated Income Taxes - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy's effective income tax rate for 2016 and 2015 was 36.0% and 36.7%, respectively. MGE's effective income tax rate for 2016 and 2015 was 35.9% and 36.7%, respectively. The decrease in the effective tax rate is due in part to a combination of individually insignificant fluctuations. See Footnote&nbsp;12 of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for details of effective income tax rates for continuing operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Noncontrolling Interest, Net of Tax - MGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	The noncontrolling interest, net of tax, reflects the accounting required for MGE&nbsp;Energy's interest in MGE Power Elm Road (the Elm Road Units) and MGE Power West Campus (WCCF). MGE&nbsp;Energy owns 100% of MGE Power Elm Road and MGE Power West Campus; however, due to the contractual agreements for these projects with MGE, the entities are considered VIEs with respect to MGE and their results are consolidated with those of MGE, the primary beneficiary of the VIEs. Also included in noncontrolling interest, net of tax, is MGE&nbsp;Energy's interest in MGE Transco, which holds our investment in ATC. The following table shows MGE&nbsp;Energy's noncontrolling interest, net of tax, reflected on MGE's consolidated statements of income:
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(a)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	MGE Transco holds an ownership interest in ATC. In July&nbsp;2016, MGE's ownership interest in MGE Transco declined below a majority, resulting in MGE&nbsp;Energy's investment in MGE Transco being deconsolidated from MGE's consolidated financial statements. See Footnote&nbsp;8 of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for further discussion of noncontrolling interest. In December&nbsp;2016, MGE's ownership interest in MGE Transco was transferred to MGE&nbsp;Energy, see Footnote&nbsp;4 of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for additional information.

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Rate changes.
</I>
	Rates charged to retail customers for 2015 were $14.4&nbsp;million or 3.6% higher than those charged during 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX">
	In December&nbsp;2014, the PSCW authorized MGE to increase 2015 rates for retail electric customers by $15.4&nbsp;million or 3.8%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Fuel Credit
</I>
	. During 2015 and 2014, customers received a fuel credit on their bill related to the fuel savings of $2.6&nbsp;million and $6.5&nbsp;million, respectively, which increased electric revenues when compared to 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-7.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Adjustments to Revenue
</I>
	. The adjustments to revenues amount includes the elimination of carrying costs for the Elm Road Units&nbsp;and the WCCF that were collected in electric rates, which are recognized as nonregulated energy operating revenues in our Nonregulated Energy Operations segment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Volume
</I>
	. During 2015, there was a 0.3% decrease in total retail sales volumes compared to 2014 primarily driven by lower use per residential customer.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Sales to the market.
</I>
	Sales to the market represent wholesale sales made to third parties who are not ultimate users of the electricity. These sales may include spot market transactions on the markets operated by MISO. These sales may also include bilateral sales to other utilities or power marketers. Generating units are dispatched by MISO based on cost considerations as well as reliability of the system. Sales to the market typically occur when MGE has more generation and purchases online than are needed for its own system demand. The excess electricity is then sold to others in the market. For 2015, market volumes increased compared to 2014, reflecting increased opportunities for sales. In addition, market settlement resulted in lower revenue per kWh for 2015, reflecting lower market prices. The revenue generated from these sales is included in fuel rules monitored costs. See fuel rules discussion in Footnote&nbsp;16.b. of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Electric fuel and purchased power
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Electric fuel and purchased power costs reflect an increase in internal generation volumes during 2015 partially offset by a decrease in the volume of purchased power when compared to 2014. Adjustments related to the regulatory recovery for fuel costs, known as fuel rules, increased purchased power expense. These items are explained below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<U>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	The decrease in expense (before fuel rules adjustments) reflects a 3.8% decrease in the per-unit cost of purchased power and a 12.8% decrease in the volume of power purchased from third parties primarily as a result of increased internal generation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Under fuel rules, MGE is required to defer electric fuel-related costs that fall outside a 2% cost tolerance band around the amount used in the most recent rate proceeding. Any fuel rules adjustments are reflected in purchased power expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

	4.0
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH=130>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For 2015, increased transmission costs are primarily related to an increase in transmission reliability enhancements. In addition, increased administrative and general costs are primarily due to increased pension and other postretirement benefits costs predominantly driven by a reduction in the discount rate, which has the effect of increasing the related costs. Decreased customer account costs are primarily related to lower uncollectible accounts receivable.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Electric depreciation expense
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Electric depreciation expense increased $3.0&nbsp;million for 2015 compared to 2014. This increase is primarily related to the completion of the Columbia environmental project. The systems and equipment for Unit&nbsp;2 and Unit&nbsp;1 were placed into service in April&nbsp;2014 and July&nbsp;2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Other Electric Income
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Other electric income decreased $2.4&nbsp;million, primarily due to AFUDC equity related to the completion of the Columbia environmental project. Unit&nbsp;2 and Unit&nbsp;1 were placed into service in April&nbsp;and July&nbsp;2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:24PX; FONT-SIZE:12PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#8226;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:24PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Volume.
</I>
	For 2015, retail gas deliveries decreased 27.0% compared to 2014, as a result of extremely cold weather experienced in the first quarter of 2014. The decrease was also attributable to a large commercial customer's decision to purchase gas from a third party supplier and to use MGE's facilities for the transport of that gas. While the shift affects revenues, the impact to gas income of this shift is not material as we do not earn margin on the natural gas commodity cost billed to customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:6PX; WIDTH:30PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:30PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-7.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Rate/PGA changes
</I>
	. In December&nbsp;2014, the PSCW approved changes to customer rates and rate design for gas service. Rates were reduced by 2.0%, effective January&nbsp;1, 2015. Gas rate design consists of a fixed monthly customer charge and a variable charge tied to actual usage, in addition to the separate charge for natural gas commodity costs that is recovered through the PGA. The change shifted more of the rate recovery to the monthly charge, reflecting the related fixed costs of providing gas services, and reduced the variable usage-based charge. Thus, gas net income was more evenly distributed during the year and less sensitive to weather.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:30PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-7.667PX">
	MGE recovers the cost of natural gas in its gas segment through the purchased gas adjustment clause (PGA). Under the PGA, MGE is able to pass through to its gas customers the cost of gas. Changes in PGA recoveries affect revenues but do not impact net income.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:30PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-7.667PX">
	The average retail rate per therm for 2015 decreased 12.8% compared to 2014, reflecting a $28.7&nbsp;million decrease in natural gas commodity costs (PGA) offset by an $8.2&nbsp;million increase (comprised of a decrease in variable rate costs offset by an increase in fixed rate charges) related to rate design changes. As noted previously, as a result of the rate design changes, revenues in the first and fourth quarters, when usage is higher, were lower than in past years; and revenues in the second and third quarters, when usage is lower, were higher than in past years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:6PX; WIDTH:30PX; FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<I>
	&#183;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:30PX; PADDING-RIGHT:-7.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<I>
	Transportation and other effects.
</I>
	During 2015, transportation and other effects increased $1.3&nbsp;million primarily attributable to a large commercial customer's decision to purchase gas from a third party supplier and to use MGE's facilities for the transport of that gas. The impact to gas income of this shift is not material.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>

</TR>

<I>
	Cost of gas sold
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For 2015, cost of gas sold decreased by $67.5&nbsp;million compared to 2014. The volume of gas purchased decreased 26.8%, which resulted in $38.5&nbsp;million of decreased expense. The cost per therm of natural gas decreased 27.6%, which resulted in $29.0&nbsp;million of decreased expense.

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For 2015, decreased customer service costs are due to lower Focus on Energy payments, Wisconsin's statewide energy efficiency and renewable resource program to promote energy efficiency on customer's premises. Decreased customer accounts costs are due to lower uncollectible accounts receivable. Increased administrative and general costs are primarily due to increased pension and other postretirement benefit costs predominantly driven by a reduction in the discount rate.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Nonregulated Energy Operations - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For 2015 and 2014, net income at the nonregulated energy operations segment was $20.1&nbsp;million and $19.3&nbsp;million, respectively. The nonregulated energy operations are conducted through MGE&nbsp;Energy's subsidiaries: MGE Power Elm Road (the Elm Road Units) and MGE Power West Campus (WCCF), which have been formed to own and lease electric generating capacity to assist MGE.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Transmission Investment Operations - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Transmission investment other income
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	For 2015 and 2014, other income at the transmission investment segment was $7.7&nbsp;million and $9.2&nbsp;million, respectively. The transmission investment segment holds our interest in ATC, and its income reflects our equity in the earnings of ATC. See Footnote&nbsp;4.b. of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements and &quot;Other Matters&quot; below for additional information concerning ATC and summarized financial information regarding ATC.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	All Other Operations - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	Other income
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	The increase in all other income primarily results from a decrease in voluntary contributions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Consolidated Income Taxes - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Both MGE&nbsp;Energy's and MGE's effective income tax rate for 2015 and 2014, was 36.7% and 37.5%, respectively. The decrease in the effective tax rate is due in part to a higher estimated domestic manufacturing deduction, offset by lower AFUDC equity earnings in 2015. See Footnote&nbsp;12 of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for details of effective income tax rates for continuing operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Noncontrolling Interest, Net of Tax - MGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	The noncontrolling interest, net of tax, reflects the accounting required for MGE&nbsp;Energy's interest in MGE Power Elm Road (the Elm Road Units) and MGE Power West Campus (WCCF). MGE&nbsp;Energy owns 100% of MGE Power Elm Road and MGE Power West Campus; however, due to the contractual agreements for these projects with MGE, the entities are considered VIEs with respect to MGE and their results are consolidated with those of MGE, the primary beneficiary of the VIEs. Also included in noncontrolling interest, net of tax, is MGE&nbsp;Energy's interest in
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT">
<B>
<I>
	Liquidity and Capital Resources
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE have adequate liquidity to fund operations and capital expenditures over the next twelve months. Available resources include cash and cash equivalents, operating cash flows, liquid assets, borrowing capacity under revolving credit facilities, and access to equity and debt capital markets.
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
	Cash Provided by Operating Activities
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	MGE&nbsp;Energy
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy's consolidated net cash provided by operating activities is derived mainly from the electric and gas operations of its principal subsidiary, MGE.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<I>
	2016 vs. 2015
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Cash provided by operating activities for 2016 was $147.5&nbsp;million, an increase of $6.3&nbsp;million when compared to the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy's net income increased $4.2&nbsp;million for 2016 when compared to the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	In both 2016 and 2015, MGE received a $10.0&nbsp;million refund from the IRS for the 2015 and 2014 tax years, respectively. Excluding the 2016 and 2015 refund, MGE&nbsp;Energy's federal and state taxes paid decreased $1.8&nbsp;million during 2016, when compared to the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Working capital accounts (excluding prepaid and accrued taxes) resulted in $5.2&nbsp;million in cash provided by operating activities for 2016, primarily due to increased accounts payable, decreased inventories, and decreased receivable margin, partially offset by increased unbilled revenues, increased receivables, and decreased current liabilities. The decrease in current liabilities includes a fuel credit, approved in August&nbsp;2015, of $8.3&nbsp;million that customers received on their bill throughout 2016 and a one-time fuel credit, approved in July&nbsp;2016, of $15.5&nbsp;million that customers received on their bill in September&nbsp;2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Working capital accounts (excluding prepaid and accrued taxes) resulted in $5.0&nbsp;million in cash provided by operating activities for 2015, primarily due to decreased receivables and decreased unbilled revenues, partially offset by increased inventories, decreased accounts payable, and decreased current liabilities. The decrease in current liabilities includes a fuel credit of $2.6&nbsp;million that customers received on their bill in the period September&nbsp;through December&nbsp;2015 related to the 2015 fuel savings and $11.4&nbsp;million of deferred fuel related cost savings to be returned to customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>

<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	39
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage40"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
<I>
	2015 vs. 2014
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Cash provided by operating activities for 2015 was $141.2&nbsp;million, an increase of $12.4&nbsp;million when compared to 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy's net income decreased $9.0&nbsp;million for 2015 when compared to 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	In 2015, MGE received a $10.0&nbsp;million refund from the IRS for the 2014 tax year. Excluding the 2015 refund, MGE&nbsp;Energy's federal and state taxes paid increased $4.7&nbsp;million during 2015 when compared to 2014. In December&nbsp;2014, bonus depreciation was extended for 2014. Tax payments were made earlier in 2014 before the additional depreciation deduction was known.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Working capital accounts (excluding prepaid and accrued taxes) resulted in $5.0&nbsp;million in cash provided by operating activities for 2015, primarily due to decreased receivables and decreased unbilled revenues, partially offset by increased inventories, decreased accounts payable, and decreased current liabilities. The decrease in current liabilities includes a fuel credit of $2.6&nbsp;million that customers received on their bill in the period September&nbsp;through December&nbsp;2015 related to the 2015 fuel savings and $11.4&nbsp;million of deferred fuel related cost savings to be returned to customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Working capital accounts (excluding prepaid and accrued taxes) resulted in $14.8&nbsp;million in cash used for operating activities for 2014, primarily due to increased gas inventories, increased other current assets, and decreased current liabilities, partially offset by increased accounts payable. The decrease in current liabilities includes a fuel credit of $6.5&nbsp;million that customers received on their bill in October&nbsp;2014 related to the 2013 fuel savings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	An increase in pension contribution resulted in an additional $10.4&nbsp;million in cash used for operating activities for 2015 when compared to 2014. Pension contributions reflect amounts required by law and discretionary amounts. See Footnote&nbsp;13 of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for further discussion of MGE&nbsp;Energy's pension and other postretirement benefits.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<B>
<I>
	MGE
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<I>
	2016 vs. 2015
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Cash provided by operating activities for 2016 was $146.5&nbsp;million, a decrease of $2.0&nbsp;million when compared to the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Net income increased $3.1&nbsp;million for 2016, when compared to the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	In both 2016 and 2015, MGE received a $10.0&nbsp;million refund from the IRS for the 2015 and 2014 tax years, respectively. Excluding the 2016 and 2015 refund, MGE's federal and state taxes paid to MGE&nbsp;Energy increased $4.2&nbsp;million during 2016, when compared to the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Working capital accounts (excluding prepaid and accrued taxes) resulted in $7.4&nbsp;million in cash provided by operating activities for 2016, primarily due to increased accounts payable, decreased inventories, and decreased receivable margin, partially offset by increased receivables, increased unbilled revenues, and decreased current liabilities. The decrease in current liabilities includes a fuel credit, that was approved in August&nbsp;2015, of $8.3&nbsp;million that customers received on their bill throughout 2016 and $15.5&nbsp;million of deferred fuel related cost savings to be returned to customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Working capital accounts (excluding prepaid and accrued taxes) resulted in $14.0&nbsp;million in cash provided by operating activities for 2015, primarily due to decreased receivables and decreased unbilled revenues, partially offset by increased gas inventories, decreased accounts payable, and decreased other current liabilities. The decrease in current liabilities includes a fuel credit of $2.6&nbsp;million that customers received on their bill in the period September&nbsp;through December&nbsp;2015 related to the 2015 fuel savings and $11.4&nbsp;million of deferred fuel related cost savings to be returned to customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<I>
	2015 vs. 2014
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Cash provided by operating activities for 2015 was $148.5&nbsp;million, an increase of $19.9&nbsp;million when compared to 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage41"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
	Net income decreased $10.5&nbsp;million for 2015 when compared to 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	In 2015, MGE received a $10.0&nbsp;million refund from the IRS for the 2014 tax year. Excluding the 2015 refund, MGE's federal and state taxes paid to MGE&nbsp;Energy decreased $3.3&nbsp;million during 2015, when compared to the prior year. In December&nbsp;2014, bonus depreciation was extended for 2014. Tax payments were made earlier in 2014 before the additional depreciation deduction was known.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Working capital accounts (excluding prepaid and accrued taxes) resulted in $14.0&nbsp;million in cash provided by operating activities for 2015, primarily due to decreased receivables and decreased unbilled revenues, partially offset by increased gas inventories, decreased accounts payable, and decreased other current liabilities. The decrease in current liabilities includes a fuel credit of $2.6&nbsp;million that customers received on their bill in the period September&nbsp;through December&nbsp;2015 related to the 2015 fuel savings and $11.4&nbsp;million of deferred fuel related cost savings to be returned to customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Working capital accounts (excluding prepaid and accrued taxes) resulted in $20.9&nbsp;million in cash used for operating activities for 2014, primarily due to increased gas inventories, increased receivables, and decreased current liabilities, partially offset by increased accounts payable. The decrease in current liabilities includes a fuel credit of $6.5&nbsp;million that customers received on their bill in October&nbsp;2014 related to the 2013 fuel savings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	An increase in pension contribution resulted in an additional $10.4&nbsp;million in cash used for operating activities for 2015 when compared to 2014. These contributions reflect amounts required by law and discretionary amounts. See Footnote&nbsp;13 of the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for further discussion of MGE's pension and other postretirement benefits.
</P>

<I>
	2016 vs. 2015
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy's cash used for investing activities increased $13.5&nbsp;million for 2016 when compared to the prior year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Capital expenditures for 2016 were $83.7&nbsp;million. This amount represents an increase of $11.6&nbsp;million from the expenditures made in the prior year. This increase primarily reflects increased expenditures on electric and gas distribution assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	There was a $1.9&nbsp;million increase in the capital contributions to investments for 2016 when compared to the prior year.

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
	Capital expenditures for 2015 were $72.0&nbsp;million. This amount represents a decrease of $20.6&nbsp;million from the expenditures made in 2014. The decrease primarily reflects $16.2&nbsp;million of lower expenditures on the Columbia environmental project in 2015 versus 2014 and decreased expenditures in electric and gas distribution assets.
</P>
