</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage65"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_1D863CADD4F94D8AB89B5C602990C940">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	l.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_A0F71CF27196467F937302A537637D0E">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Repairs and Maintenance Expense - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE utilizes the direct expensing method for planned major maintenance projects. Under this method, MGE expenses all costs associated with major planned maintenance activities as incurred.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_31FAD33B0C3242C884D0AD8DCFBF9FD6">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	m.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_1DBDEDC5D1BD48D3BDB91925C5AE6527">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Purchased Gas Adjustment Clause - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE's natural gas rates are subject to a fuel adjustment clause designed to recover or refund the difference between the actual cost of purchased gas and the amount included in rates. Differences between the amounts billed to customers and the actual costs recoverable are deferred and recovered or refunded in future periods by means of prospective monthly adjustments to rates. At December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, MGE had over collected $0.9&nbsp;million and $0.8&nbsp;million, respectively.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_2DB75BAA451949E3BEFD77D9904B6750">
</A>
	These amounts are included in &quot;Regulatory liabilities - current&quot; on the consolidated balance sheets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_C22B168608634F44B09A4CDDAD192448">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	n.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_D38B0D392FB14FD882D2F39EC2E6DCF6">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Revenue Recognition - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Operating revenues are recorded as service is rendered or energy is delivered to customers. Meters are read on a systematic basis throughout the month based on established meter-reading schedules. At the end of the month, MGE accrues an estimate for the unbilled amount of energy delivered to customers. The unbilled revenue estimate is based on daily system demand volumes, weather factors, estimated line losses, estimated customer usage by class, and applicable customer rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_772AF1A36DEB4AD5850677D2BB9B0C0C">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	o.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_34448FFE09D448C4BB83A86809781346">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Utility Cost Recovery - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE's rates include a provision for fuel costs. The PSCW allows Wisconsin utilities to defer electric fuel-related costs, less excess revenues, that fall outside a symmetrical cost tolerance band. Any over/under recovery of the actual costs in a year is determined in the following year and is then reflected in future billings to electric retail customers. Such deferred amounts will be recognized in &quot;Purchased power&quot; expense in MGE&nbsp;Energy's and MGE's consolidated income statements each period. The cumulative effects of these deferred amounts will be recorded in &quot;Regulatory assets&quot; or &quot;Regulatory liabilities&quot; on MGE&nbsp;Energy's and MGE's consolidated balance sheets until they are reflected in future billings to customers. See Footnote&nbsp;16.b. for further information regarding the regulatory rules applicable to the recovery of electric fuel costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_5DA1E51EC5744B45B4AF9CD002D84089">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	p.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_0E1559A282AC48BBBB6147B1C66C7285">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Regional Transmission Organizations - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE reports on a net basis transactions on the MISO markets in which it buys and sells power within the same hour to meet electric energy delivery requirements. This treatment resulted in a $77.2&nbsp;million, a $68.6&nbsp;million, and a $91.1&nbsp;million reduction to sales to the market and purchase power expense for MISO markets for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015, and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_AD85857540394013B1C51C9E26A1D66C">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	q.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_5346490873A9417997449F679E61F460">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Allowance for Funds Used During Construction - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Allowance for funds used during construction is included in utility plant accounts and represents the cost of borrowed funds used during plant construction and a return on shareholder's capital used for construction purposes. In the consolidated income statements, the cost of borrowed funds (AFUDC-debt) is presented as an offset to &quot;Interest expense&quot; and the return on shareholder's capital (AFUDC-equity funds) is shown as an item within &quot;Other income.&quot; For both 2016 and 2015, as approved by the PSCW, MGE capitalized AFUDC-debt and equity on 50% of applicable average construction work in progress at 7.93%. For 2014, MGE capitalized AFUDC-debt and equity on 50% of applicable average construction work in progress at 8.21%. For 2016, 2015, and 2014, MGE received specific approval to recover 100% AFUDC on certain environmental costs for Columbia. These amounts are recovered under the ratemaking process over the service lives of the related properties.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_9394BAF1E8EC425A92D63A97C03A95E2">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	r.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_02D87459DE624C3193F57CADD72D9270">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Investments - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Investments in limited liability companies that have specific ownership accounts in which MGE&nbsp;Energy or MGE's ownership interest is more than minor and are considered to have significant influence are accounted for using the equity method. All other investments are carried at fair value or at cost, as appropriate. See Footnote&nbsp;4 for further information.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>

</TR>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage66"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_56B135E7EA794D78AC7F1C0C49BFE264">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	s.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TAG82">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_0E91C8815D534BBCA95430D0D58A1E4B">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Capitalized Software Costs - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Property, plant, and equipment includes the net book value of capitalized costs of internal use software totaling $12.3&nbsp;million and $12.0&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, respectively. During 2016, 2015, and 2014, MGE recorded $3.0&nbsp;million, $2.2&nbsp;million, and $1.6&nbsp;million, respectively, of amortization expense related to these costs. These costs are amortized on a straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives of the assets. For internal use software, the useful lives range from five to ten years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_18F3630CCF854BCB96F3DF4E3413978E">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	t.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_3EF7E689022841D4BB0942F735306EF1">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Impairment of Long-Lived Assets - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE reviews plant and equipment and other property for impairment when events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of the assets may not be recoverable. MGE's policy for determining when long-lived assets are impaired is to recognize an impairment loss if the sum of the expected future cash flows (undiscounted and without interest charges) from an asset are less than the carrying amount of that asset. If an impairment loss is recognized, the amount that will be recorded will be measured as the amount by which the carrying amount of the asset exceeds the fair value of the asset. There is no impairment of long-lived assets at December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015, and 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_594CF08D7190403BAAFE8D5B009F41C4">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	u.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_FDEBA880DD364410B9730A574B4D433A">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Income Taxes and Excise Taxes - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
<I>
	Income taxes
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Under the liability method, income taxes are deferred for all temporary differences between pretax financial and taxable income and between the book and tax basis of assets and liabilities using the tax rates scheduled by law to be in effect when the temporary differences reverse. Future tax benefits are recognized to the extent that realization of such benefits is more likely than not. A valuation allowance is recorded for those benefits that do not meet this criterion.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Accounting for uncertainty in income taxes applies to all tax positions and requires a recognition threshold and measurement standard for the financial statement recognition and measurement of a tax position taken, or expected to be taken, in an income tax return. The threshold is defined for recognizing tax return positions in the financial statements as &quot;more likely than not&quot; that the position is sustainable, based on its merits. Subsequent recognition, derecognition, and measurement is based on management's best judgment given the facts, circumstances, and information available at the reporting date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Regulatory and accounting principles have resulted in a regulatory liability related to income taxes. Excess deferred income taxes result from past taxes provided at rates higher than current rates. The income tax regulatory liability and deferred investment tax credit reflect the revenue requirement associated with the return of these tax benefits to customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Investment tax credits from regulated operations are amortized over related property service lives.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_520553DE3D3F404EA8F8E9001A8B2268">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
<I>
	Excise taxes
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy, through its utility operations, pays a state license fee tax in lieu of property taxes on property used in utility operations. License fee tax is calculated as a percentage of adjusted operating revenues of the prior year. The electric tax rate is 3.19% for retail sales and 1.59% for sales of electricity for resale by the purchaser. The tax rate on sales of natural gas is 0.97%. The tax is required to be estimated and prepaid in the year prior to its computation and expensing. License fee tax expense, included in &quot;Other general taxes,&quot; was $14.5&nbsp;million, $14.7&nbsp;million, and $14.6&nbsp;million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015, and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Operating income taxes, including tax credits and license fee tax, are included in rates for utility related items.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_BECAC93112EF46129B09A2346B73BD21">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	v.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_46C50433DA2144569A22506EA45509C1">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Share-Based Compensation - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Under two separate incentive plans, eligible participants, including employees and non-employee directors, may receive performance units that entitle the holder to receive a cash payment equal to the value of a designated number of shares of MGE&nbsp;Energy's common stock, plus dividend equivalent payments thereon, at the end of the set performance period. Under the plans, these awards are subject to
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	66
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage67"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
	a&nbsp;prescribed vesting schedule and must be settled in cash. Accordingly, no new shares of common stock are issued in connection with the plans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE initially measure the cost of the employee or director services received in exchange for a performance unit award based on the current market value of MGE&nbsp;Energy common stock. The fair value of the award is subsequently re-measured at each reporting date through the settlement date. Changes in fair value during the requisite period are recognized as compensation cost over that period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	See Footnote&nbsp;14 for additional information regarding the plans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_9B7807BE2F9E4829A2860CB9F922D27C">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	w.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_845CBC2921CD409183A4F43BB94C8286">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Comprehensive Income - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Total comprehensive income includes all changes in equity during a period except those resulting from investments by and distributions to shareholders. Comprehensive income is reflected in the consolidated statements of comprehensive income.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_2EC7A4E2AB3F4C429A07902C4BC0F2B3">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	x.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_6099092E022D4EE1A287276E49BD565C">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Derivative and Hedging Instruments - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	As part of regular operations, MGE enters into contracts, including options, swaps, futures, forwards, and other contractual commitments, to manage its exposure to commodity prices. MGE recognizes all derivatives in the consolidated balance sheets at fair value, with changes in the fair value of derivative instruments to be recorded in current earnings or deferred in accumulated other comprehensive income (loss), depending on whether a derivative is designated as, and is effective as, a hedge and on the type of hedge transaction. Derivative activities are in accordance with the company's risk management policy.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	If the derivative qualifies for regulatory deferral, the derivatives are marked to fair value and are offset with a corresponding regulatory asset or liability. Cash flows from such derivative instruments are classified on a basis consistent with the nature of the underlying hedged item.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:36PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	2.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_EF60E984DF2449538C2BF3610C9BD5DD">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Variable Interest Entities - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	a.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	MGE Power Elm Road.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE Power Elm Road is not a subsidiary of MGE; however, it has been consolidated in the financial statements of MGE. MGE Power Elm Road was created for the purpose of owning new generating assets. Its sole principal assets are an undivided ownership interest in two coal-fired generating plants located in Oak Creek, Wisconsin, which it leases to MGE pursuant to long-term leases. Based on the nature and terms of the contractual agreements, MGE is expected to absorb a majority of the expected losses, residual value, or both, associated with the ownership of MGE Power Elm Road and therefore holds a variable interest in MGE Power Elm Road, even though it has no equity interest in MGE Power Elm Road. MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE consolidate VIEs for which they are the primary beneficiary. MGE has the power to direct the activities that most significantly impact the Elm Road Units' economic performance and is also the party most closely associated with MGE Power Elm Road. As a result, MGE is the primary beneficiary.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_A7547B6E39C84971916873FD959A969F">
</A>
	At December&nbsp;31, MGE has included the following significant accounts on its consolidated balance sheets related to its interest in this VIE:
</P>

<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_FD5CD5E03BCD47DB8B638CE66B5D96B0">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Long-term debt excluding debt issuance costs consists of $62.6&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2016, of senior secured notes that require that MGE Power Elm Road maintain a projected and actual debt service coverage ratio at the end of any calendar quarter of not less than 1.25 to 1.00 for the trailing 12-month period. The debt is secured by a collateral assignment of lease payments that MGE is making to MGE Power Elm Road for use of the Elm Road Units&nbsp;pursuant to the related long-term leases. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE Power Elm Road is in compliance with the covenant requirements.
</P>

<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	67
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage68"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
	MGE has been and will continue to recover in rates the lease payments made to MGE Power Elm Road. MGE received approval from the PSCW to collect in rates the carrying costs incurred by MGE Power Elm Road. The total carrying costs on the Elm Road Units&nbsp;is $62.5&nbsp;million. MGE collected carrying costs in rates over a six year period that began in 2010. Of these costs, $17.0&nbsp;million relates to the capitalized interest and the debt portion of the units. These costs will be recognized over the period in which the generating units will be depreciated. The remaining $45.5&nbsp;million represents the equity portion and was recognized over the period allowed for recovery in rates which ended in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_11C1D08BD6AD44BB9FB4AE61D3390D82">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	b.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	MGE Power West Campus.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE Power West Campus is not a subsidiary of MGE; however, it has been consolidated in the financial statements of MGE. MGE Power West Campus was created for the purpose of owning new generating assets. Its sole principal asset is the WCCF, which it leases to MGE pursuant to a long-term lease. MGE is responsible for operation of the plant during the term of the lease. Based on the nature and terms of these contractual relationships, MGE absorbs a majority of the expected losses, residual value, or both, associated with the ownership and operation of the WCCF and therefore holds a variable interest in MGE Power West Campus, even though it has no equity interest in MGE Power West Campus. MGE has the power to direct the activities that most significantly impact WCCF's economic performance and is also the party most closely associated with MGE Power West Campus. As a result, MGE is the primary beneficiary.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_5137306F8D5E49328CC0C6BB4ECD669A">
</A>
	At December&nbsp;31, MGE has included the following significant accounts on its consolidated balance sheets related to its interest in this VIE:
</P>

<TD WIDTH=127 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH=127>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING:0PX">
	&nbsp;

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_AF7F71372454428A897D5BB08227B243">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Long-term debt excluding debt issuance costs consists of $45.1&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2016, of senior secured notes that require that MGE Power West Campus maintain a projected debt service coverage ratio of not less than 1.25 to 1.00 and debt to total capitalization ratio of not more than 0.65 to 1.00. The debt is secured by a collateral assignment of lease payments that MGE is making to MGE Power West Campus for use of the cogeneration facility pursuant to the long-term lease. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE Power West Campus is in compliance with the covenant requirements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE has been and will continue to recover lease payments made to MGE Power West Campus in rates. Also, MGE received approval from the PSCW to collect approximately $12.1&nbsp;million in carrying costs incurred by MGE Power West Campus during construction of the facility. The carrying costs were recovered in rates over a 10 year period that started in 2005 and ended in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_105C2765257F4C2BAFFDB21B5570FB4E">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	c.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Other Variable Interest Entities.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE has a variable interest in entities through purchase power agreements relating to purchased energy from the facilities covered by the agreements. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, MGE had 51 megawatts and 61 megawatts, respectively, of capacity available under these agreements. MGE evaluated the variable interest entities for possible consolidation. The interest holder is considered the primary beneficiary of the entity and is required to consolidate the entity if the interest holder has the power to direct the activities that most significantly impact the economics of the variable interest entity. MGE examined qualitative factors such as the length of the remaining term of the contracts compared with the remaining lives of the plants, who has the power to direct the operations and maintenance of the facilities, and other factors, and determined MGE is not the primary beneficiary of the variable interest entities. There is not a significant potential exposure to loss as a result of involvement with these variable interest entities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>

<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_45C0D11471A547F99FB9A9BC238F57C9">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:60PX; WIDTH:84PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(a)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_A69B15D45AB341B283E8BBA441EB2244">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	MGE Transco holds an ownership interest in ATC, and MGEE Transco holds an ownership interest in ATC Holdco. In July&nbsp;2016, MGE's ownership interest in MGE Transco declined below a majority, resulting in MGE&nbsp;Energy's investment in MGE Transco being deconsolidated from MGE's consolidated financial statements. See Footnote&nbsp;8 for further discussion of noncontrolling interest. In December&nbsp;2016, MGE's ownership interest in MGE Transco was transferred to MGE&nbsp;Energy, see &quot;ATC and ATC Holdco&quot; below for additional information.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy's and MGE's available for sale securities represent publicly traded securities and private equity investments in common stock of companies in various industries.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_BF0677D9EAAC400BA5C3C18487367E59">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	b.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	ATC and ATC Holdco.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	ATC owns and operates electric transmission facilities primarily in Wisconsin. MGE received an interest in ATC when it, like other Wisconsin electric utilities, contributed its electric transmission facilities to ATC as required by Wisconsin law. That interest is presently held by MGE Transco, which, as of December&nbsp;1, 2016, is owned by MGE&nbsp;Energy. ATC Holdco was formed by several members of ATC, including MGE&nbsp;Energy, to pursue electric transmission development and investments outside of Wisconsin. The ownership interest in ATC Holdco is held by MGEE Transco, a wholly-owned subsidiary of MGE&nbsp;Energy.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE Transco and MGEE Transco have accounted for their investment in ATC and ATC Holdco, respectively, under the equity method of accounting.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_C0BE124B3ED847ACB1109BF8E7AA11E2">
</A>
	For the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015, and 2014, MGE Transco recorded the following:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_E16102A1448748689456CD7C100B09D1">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_8440F284417F4E77BC50E0D4A0C99B48">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:60PX; WIDTH:84PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(a)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_D0AD653E4B834EDCBF622DE457F17BA3">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE Transco recorded a $2.1&nbsp;million receivable from ATC for a cash dividend received in January&nbsp;2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	ATC Holdco's activities commenced in late December&nbsp;2016 and had an immaterial impact on results of operations, cash flows, and financial condition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, MGE Transco held a 3.6% ownership interest in ATC. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGEE Transco held a 4.0% ownership interest in ATC Holdco. On January&nbsp;31, 2017, MGE Transco made a $1.4&nbsp;million capital contribution to ATC, and on January&nbsp;10, 2017, MGEE Transco made a $0.2&nbsp;million capital contribution to ATC Holdco.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	In June&nbsp;2016, the PSCW required MGE to transfer its interest in ATC to MGE&nbsp;Energy, which was to be completed by December&nbsp;31, 2022. The requirement arose in the context of requests for regulatory approvals by several owners of ATC in connection with a reorganization of ATC. MGE's ownership interest in ATC, held through MGE Transco, was transferred net of deferred tax liabilities to MGE&nbsp;Energy by way of a dividend in kind of $15.8&nbsp;million as of December&nbsp;1, 2016. As a result of the transfer, MGE's ownership interest in MGE Transco was completely eliminated in favor of MGE&nbsp;Energy. See Footnote&nbsp;12 for further discussion of the transfer of deferred tax liabilities. The change had no effect on MGE&nbsp;Energy's consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_6FF241F006F743C990D3905E98545AE5">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_C011D7FDDF934B9D9719D211DF2EC481">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>

<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:36PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	5.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_AF1D19D756C040E589F70EC4274E3CFD">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Joint Plant Ownership - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	a.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Columbia.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX">
	MGE and two other utilities jointly own Columbia, a coal-fired generating facility located in Portage, Wisconsin, which, at December&nbsp;31, 2016, accounts for 30% (225&nbsp;MW) of MGE's net summer rated capacity. Power from this facility is shared in proportion to each company's ownership interest. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE had a 22.0% ownership interest in Columbia. The other owners are WPL, which operates Columbia, and WPSC. MGE's share of fuel, operating, and maintenance expenses for Columbia was $39.5&nbsp;million, $38.2&nbsp;million, and $28.1&nbsp;million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015, and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX">
	Each owner provides its own financing and reflects its respective portion of facilities and operating costs in its financial statements.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_44458F40F4E04776935D35DBF4F23B15">
</A>
	MGE's interest in Columbia's gross utility plant in service, and the related accumulated depreciation reserves at December&nbsp;31 were as follows:
</P>

<BR>
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_29D7E29E6BA14B64B313EE040C02B808">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	In 2016, MGE and WPL negotiated an amendment to the existing Columbia joint operating agreement, that has been approved by the PSCW, under which MGE will have the option to reduce its obligation to pay certain capital expenditures (other than SCR-related expenditures) at Columbia in exchange for a proportional reduction in MGE's ownership in Columbia. On January&nbsp;1 of each year, beginning in 2017 and ending June&nbsp;1, 2020, the ownership percentage will be adjusted, through a partial sale, based on the amount of capital expenditures foregone. In December&nbsp;2016, MGE jointly filed a request with the co-owners of Columbia for FERC approval of the amendment to the Columbia joint operating agreement, effective January&nbsp;1, 2017. MGE currently expects to receive FERC's decision on the amendment in 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	During 2016, MGE accrued $14.8&nbsp;million of 2016 capital expenditures that MGE has forgone as part of the ownership transfer agreement with WPL. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE classified $14.8&nbsp;million of Columbia assets as held-for-sale on the consolidated balance sheets. In January&nbsp;2017, MGE reduced its ownership interest in Columbia from 22.0% to 20.4% through the partial sale of plant assets to WPL.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_A9ABB6FE186B41F9BDE66A7129A05461">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	71
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage72"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	b.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Elm Road.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE Power Elm Road owns an 8.33% ownership interest in each of two 615&nbsp;MW coal-fired generating units in Oak Creek, Wisconsin, which, at December&nbsp;31, 2016, accounts for 14% (106&nbsp;MW) of MGE's net summer rated capacity. Unit&nbsp;1 entered commercial operation on February&nbsp;2, 2010. Unit&nbsp;2 entered commercial operation on January&nbsp;12, 2011. MGE Power Elm Road's sole principal asset is that ownership interest in those generating units. MGE Power Elm Road's interest in the Elm Road Units&nbsp;is leased to MGE pursuant to long-term leases.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	The remainder of the ownership interest in the Elm Road Units&nbsp;is held by two other entities, one of which is also responsible for the Units' operation. Each owner provides its own financing and reflects its respective portion of the facility and costs in its financial statements. MGE's share of fuel, operating, and maintenance expenses for the Elm Road Units&nbsp;was $21.2&nbsp;million, $20.9&nbsp;million, and $20.3&nbsp;million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015, and 2014, respectively.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_D4F420C510264E1A99E1BF76DF0B53C7">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_A18EA86521734794AA8D1D5B66B774CE">
</A>
	MGE Power Elm Road's interest in the portion of the Elm Road Units&nbsp;in-service and the related accumulated depreciation reserves at December&nbsp;31 were as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>

<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_78B4790580A74D31852D32A817A03AB3">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	c.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	WCCF.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE Power West Campus and the UW jointly own the West Campus Cogeneration Facility located on the UW campus in Madison, Wisconsin. MGE Power West Campus owns 55% of the facility and the UW owns 45% of the facility. The UW owns a controlling interest in the chilled-water and steam plants, which are used to meet the growing needs for air-conditioning and steam-heat capacity for the UW campus. MGE Power West Campus owns a controlling interest in the electric generation plant, which is leased and operated by MGE.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Each owner provides its own financing and reflects its respective portion of the facility and operating costs in its financial statements.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_A2B525C98C684107930BE099EF45F2F5">
</A>
	MGE Power West Campus' interest in WCCF and the related accumulated depreciation reserves at December&nbsp;31 were as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Operating charges are allocated to the UW based on formulas contained in the operating agreement. Under the provisions of this arrangement, the UW is required to reimburse MGE for their allocated portion of fuel and operating expenses. For the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015, and 2014, the UW allocated share of fuel and operating costs was $5.5&nbsp;million, $3.7&nbsp;million, and $2.8&nbsp;million, respectively.

<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH=10>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:9PT" ALIGN=RIGHT>
	$
</P>
</TD>

</I>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH=10>

	29,083
</P>

	$

</TD>

	30,300
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH=73>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_43703EFACF8C4C0AAA2FB40BFCDA2B8B">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	MGE expects to recover its regulatory assets and return its regulatory liabilities through rates charged to customers based on PSCW decisions made during the ratemaking process or based on PSCW long-standing policies and guidelines. The adjustments to rates for these regulatory assets and liabilities will occur over the periods either specified by the PSCW or over the corresponding period related to the asset or liability. Management believes it is probable that MGE will continue to recover from customers the regulatory assets described above based on prior and current ratemaking treatment for such costs. All regulatory assets for which a cash outflow had been made are earning a return, except for amounts expended for environmental costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Asset Retirement Obligation
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	See Footnote&nbsp;18 for further discussion.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Conservation Costs
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	MGE has received regulatory treatment for certain conservation expenditures. The expenditures are used for Focus on Energy programs, Wisconsin's statewide energy efficiency and renewable resource program, to promote energy efficiency on the customer's premises. Costs for Focus on Energy programs are estimated in MGE's rates utilizing escrow accounting. The escrow accounting allows the utility to true-up its actual costs incurred and reflect the amount of the true-up in its next rate case filing.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Debt Related Costs
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	This balance includes debt issuance costs of extinguished debt and other debt related expenses, including make-whole premiums. The PSCW has allowed rate recovery on unamortized issuance costs for extinguished debt facilities. When the facility replacing the old facility is deemed by the PSCW to be more favorable for the ratepayers, the PSCW will allow rate recovery of any unamortized issuance costs related to the old facility. These amounts are recovered over the term of the new facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Derivatives
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	MGE has physical and financial contracts that are defined as derivatives. The amounts recorded for the net mark-to-market value of the commodity based contracts is offset with a corresponding regulatory asset or liability because these transactions are part of the PGA or fuel rules clause authorized by the PSCW. A significant portion of the recorded amount is related to a purchased power agreement that provides MGE with firm capacity and energy during a base term from June&nbsp;1, 2012, through May&nbsp;31, 2022. This agreement is accounted for as a derivative contract. See Footnote&nbsp;15 for further discussion.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	73
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage74"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
<B>
<I>
	Environmental Costs
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	MGE has been allowed to defer actual costs on certain environmental matters, including clean up of two landfill sites and legal expenditures pertaining to the response to the EPA Clean Air Act enforcement matter at Columbia. For further discussion of the Columbia Clean Air Act litigation, see Footnote&nbsp;17.c.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Tax Recovery Related to AFUDC Equity
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	AFUDC equity represents the after-tax equity cost associated with utility plant construction and results in a temporary difference between the book and tax basis of such plant. It is probable under PSCW regulation that MGE will recover in future rates the future increase in taxes payable represented by the deferred income tax liability. The amounts will be recovered in rates over the depreciable life of the asset for which AFUDC was applied. Tax recovery related to AFUDC equity represents the revenue requirement related to recovery of these future taxes payable, calculated at current statutory tax rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Unfunded Pension and Other Postretirement Liability
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	MGE is required to recognize the unfunded status of defined benefit pension and other postretirement pension plans as a net liability or asset on the balance sheet with an offset to a regulatory asset or liability. The unfunded status represents future expenses that are expected to be recovered in rates. See Footnote&nbsp;13 for further discussion.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Deferred Fuel Savings
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	The fuel rules require the PSCW and Wisconsin utilities to defer electric fuel-related costs that fall outside a symmetrical cost tolerance band. Any over/under recovery of the actual costs is determined on an annual basis and is adjusted in future billings to electric retail customers. See Footnote&nbsp;16.b. for further discussion.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Elm Road
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	Costs associated with Elm Road are estimated in MGE's rates utilizing escrow accounting and include costs for lease payments, management fees, community impact mitigation, and operating costs. Also, MGE has deferred payments made to MGE Power Elm Road for carrying costs during construction of the facility. MGE has collected the carrying costs in rates over a six year period that ended in 2015. All other costs are collected in rates over a one to two year period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	Excess deferred income taxes result from past taxes provided at rates higher than current rates. The regulatory liability and deferred investment tax credit reflects the revenue requirement associated with the return of these tax benefits to customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Non-ARO Removal Costs
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	In connection with accounting for asset retirement obligations, companies are required to reclassify cumulative collections for non-ARO removal costs as a regulatory liability, with an offsetting entry to accumulated depreciation. Under the current rate structure, these removal costs are being recovered as a component of depreciation expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
<B>
<I>
	Renewable Energy Credits
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	MGE receives renewable energy credits from certain purchase power agreements. The value of the credits are recorded as inventory and expensed when the credit is redeemed or expired. A regulatory liability has been established for the value of the renewable energy credits included in inventory. In Wisconsin, renewable energy credits expire four years after the year of acquisition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:36PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	7.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_6890D9620A7C4EB79D38F3F939EF68D8">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Common Equity.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	a.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Common Stock - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	On December&nbsp;20, 2013, MGE&nbsp;Energy's Board of Directors declared a three-for-two stock split of MGE&nbsp;Energy's outstanding shares of common stock, effective in the form of a stock dividend. Shareholders of record at the close of business on January&nbsp;24, 2014, received one additional share of MGE&nbsp;Energy common stock for every two shares of common stock owned on that date. The additional shares were distributed on February&nbsp;7, 2014. Shareholders received cash in lieu of any fractional shares of common stock they otherwise would have received in connection with the dividend. All share and per share data provided in this report give effect to this stock split.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_479B5076004C48ECB06937DDA326739B">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	74
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage75"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy sells shares of its common stock through its Stock Plan. Those shares may be newly issued shares or shares that MGE&nbsp;Energy has purchased in the open market for resale to participants in the Stock Plan. All sales under the Stock Plan are covered by a shelf registration statement that MGE&nbsp;Energy filed with the SEC. For the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, MGE&nbsp;Energy did not issue any new shares of common stock under the Stock Plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_9B560CAB4B19445DBF9632F392000401">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy purchases shares on the open market to provide shares to meet obligations to participants in the Stock Plan. The shares are purchased on the open market through a securities broker-dealer and then are reissued under the Stock Plan as needed to meet share delivery requirements. The volume and timing of share repurchases in the open market depends upon the level of dividend reinvestment and optional share purchases being made from time to time by plan participants. As a result, there is no specific maximum number of shares to be repurchased and no specified termination date for the repurchases.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	During the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, MGE&nbsp;Energy paid $41.8&nbsp;million (or $1.21 per share) and $40.0&nbsp;million (or $1.16 per share), respectively, in cash dividends on its common stock. Dividend payments by MGE to MGE&nbsp;Energy are subject to restrictions arising under a PSCW rate order and, to a lesser degree, MGE's first mortgage bonds. The PSCW order restricts any dividends, above the PSCW authorized amount that MGE may pay MGE&nbsp;Energy if its common equity ratio, calculated in the manner used in the rate proceeding, is less than 55%. See Footnote&nbsp;9 for further discussion of the mortgage indenture covenants. During the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, MGE paid $50.0&nbsp;million and $30.0&nbsp;million, respectively, in cash dividends to MGE&nbsp;Energy. In 2016, MGE also transferred its ownership interest in MGE Transco to MGE&nbsp;Energy in the form of a dividend in kind of $15.8&nbsp;million. See Footnote&nbsp;4 for further information.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	b.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Dilutive Shares Calculation - MGE&nbsp;Energy.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy does not hold any dilutive securities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:36PX; FLOAT:LEFT">

<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_DC01299EB6844795BB35CA510C34E717">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_FA46CC970D4849E998DD9E2838475C31">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_C3D282508E364C62AE88AD39D0094AC9">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_028BDDAF05AA4D8F86A35752D0DFDFCB">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_7292E559105F4A4CB0A5E2C1DEDEC896">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36.467PX; WIDTH:60.467PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(a)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_24E0B9E65EDE4273AA0F60751857FC34">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	MGE Power Elm Road and MGE Power West Campus are not subsidiaries of MGE; however, they have been consolidated in the consolidated financial statements of MGE (see Footnote&nbsp;2). MGE Power Elm Road and MGE Power West Campus are 100% owned by MGE Power, and MGE Power is 100% owned by MGE&nbsp;Energy. MGE&nbsp;Energy's proportionate share of the equity and net income (through its wholly owned subsidiary MGE Power) of MGE Power Elm Road and MGE Power West Campus is classified within the MGE consolidated financial statements as noncontrolling interest.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36.467PX; WIDTH:60.467PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(b)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_EB61A78A5C4C4FBEAD33DF6FBB4CC049">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE&nbsp;Energy is the owner of MGE Transco. In July&nbsp;2016, MGE's ownership interest in MGE Transco declined below a majority as a result of continued funding of ATC capital contributions by MGE&nbsp;Energy. As a result of the change in majority ownership in MGE Transco, MGE deconsolidated MGE&nbsp;Energy's proportionate share of the equity in MGE Transco. The change in consolidation was applied prospectively by reducing its investment and noncontrolling interest on MGE's consolidated financial statements. The change had no effect on MGE&nbsp;Energy's consolidated financial
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	75
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage76"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
	statements; however, MGE&nbsp;Energy's proportionate share of the equity and net income of MGE Transco classified as noncontrolling interest was deconsolidated from MGE's financial statements. No gain or loss was recognized in July&nbsp;2016 due to MGE ceasing to have a controlling financial interest.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_3540AF7818164D4BA4FDE67F4E115913">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_7D7C6A428EAF44E191F090355059D35D">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:62PX; WIDTH:84PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(a)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_3A4E4B224C9B4D5895F2C2A2E5D14E85">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	MGE's utility plant is subject to the lien of its Indenture of Mortgage and Deed of Trust, under which its first mortgage bonds are issued. The Mortgage Indenture provides that dividends or any other distribution or purchase of shares may not be made if the aggregate amount thereof since December&nbsp;31, 1945 would exceed the earned surplus (retained earnings) accumulated subsequent to December&nbsp;31, 1945. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, approximately $338.5&nbsp;million was available for the payment of dividends under this covenant.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:60.467PX; WIDTH:84PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(b)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_EEC5100243BB41EB8D6E5D8B19BE28CF">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	The indenture under which MGE's Medium-Term notes are issued provides that those notes will be entitled to be equally and ratably secured in the event that MGE issues any additional first mortgage bonds.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:60.467PX; WIDTH:84PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(c)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_6A2FAFCB5772435ABDB6E1BF2528A41C">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	MGE had $30&nbsp;million of medium-term notes mature in January&nbsp;2017. MGE issued $40&nbsp;million of new long-term unsecured debt on January&nbsp;13, 2017, to refinance the maturing $30&nbsp;million medium-term notes and assist with the financing of additional capital expenditures. The new debt carries an interest rate of 3.76% per annum over its 35-year term. The covenants of this debt are substantially consistent with MGE's existing unsecured long-term debt. In accordance with applicable accounting guidance, MGE has classified the $30&nbsp;million of maturing medium-term notes as long-term debt on the consolidated balance sheets for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>

<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">

</TR>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	76

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage77"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:60.467PX; WIDTH:84PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(d)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_0F711940095341E39E0725F21BA83048">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Unsecured notes issued pursuant to various Note Purchase Agreements with one or more purchasers. The notes are not issued under, or governed by, MGE's Indenture dated as of September&nbsp;1, 1998, which governs MGE's Medium-Term Notes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:60PX; WIDTH:84PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(e)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_366B314BC0584094A791280EB67295EC">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Issued by MGE. Under that Note Purchase Agreement: (i) note holders have the right to require MGE to repurchase their notes at par in the event of an acquisition of beneficial ownership of 30% or more of the outstanding voting stock of MGE&nbsp;Energy, (ii) MGE must maintain a ratio of its consolidated indebtedness to consolidated total capitalization not to exceed a maximum of 65%, and (iii) MGE cannot issue &quot;Priority Debt&quot; in an amount exceeding 20% of its consolidated assets. Priority Debt is defined as any indebtedness of MGE secured by liens other than specified liens permitted by the Note Purchase Agreement and certain unsecured indebtedness of certain subsidiaries. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE was in compliance with the covenant requirements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:60PX; WIDTH:84PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(f)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_AD1584911A214813A4F6DF3FD48B680C">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Issued by MGE Power West Campus. The Note Purchase Agreements require it to maintain a projected debt service coverage ratio of not less than 1.25 to 1.00, and debt to total capitalization ratio of not more than 0.65 to 1.00. The notes are secured by a collateral assignment of lease payments that MGE is making to MGE Power West Campus for use of its ownership interest in the WCCF pursuant to a long-term lease. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE Power West Campus was in compliance with the covenant requirements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:60PX; WIDTH:84PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(g)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_D3CACCEABE79462D90D9DBE85888FA3C">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	Issued by MGE Power Elm Road. The Note Purchase Agreement requires MGE Power Elm Road to maintain a projected and actual debt service coverage ratio at the end of any calendar quarter of not less than 1.25 to 1.00 for the trailing 12-month period. The notes are secured by a collateral assignment of lease payments that MGE is making to MGE Power Elm Road for use of its ownership interest in the Elm Road Units&nbsp;pursuant to long-term leases. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE Power Elm Road was in compliance with the covenant requirements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	b.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Long-Term Debt Maturities.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">

</A>

	Below is MGE&nbsp;Energy's and MGE's aggregate maturities for all long-term debt for years following December&nbsp;31, 2016.

<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_DA8D034A8A4B411B8F538FCB5ACF5BB1">

<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_BAE4144F0F8940FE964F1353603FA364">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:72PX">
<I>
	*Includes $45.1&nbsp;million for MGE Power West Campus and $62.6&nbsp;million for MGE Power Elm Road, all of which are consolidated with MGE's debt (see Footnote&nbsp;2 for further information)
</I>
	.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:36PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	10.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_272A28D1C9354487A556770ADB8FCD12">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Notes Payable to Banks, Commercial Paper, and Lines of Credit.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	a.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	MGE&nbsp;Energy.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; PADDING-RIGHT:1.2PX">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE&nbsp;Energy had an unsecured, committed revolving line of credit of $50&nbsp;million expiring June&nbsp;1, 2020. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, no borrowings were outstanding under this facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	The agreement requires MGE&nbsp;Energy to maintain a ratio of its consolidated indebtedness to consolidated total capitalization not to exceed a maximum of 65%. A change in control constitutes a default under the agreement. Change in control events are defined as (i) a failure by MGE&nbsp;Energy to hold 100% of the outstanding voting equity interest in MGE or (ii) the acquisition of beneficial ownership of 30% or more of the outstanding voting stock of MGE&nbsp;Energy by one person or two or more persons acting in concert. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE&nbsp;Energy was in compliance with the covenant requirements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	77
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage78"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	b.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	For short-term borrowings, MGE generally issues commercial paper (issued at the prevailing discount rate at the time of issuance), which is supported by unused committed bank lines of credit. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE had two unsecured, committed revolving lines of credit for a total of $100&nbsp;million expiring June&nbsp;1, 2020. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, no borrowings were outstanding under these facilities, and MGE had no commercial paper outstanding.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	The agreements require MGE to maintain a ratio of consolidated debt to consolidated total capitalization not to exceed a maximum of 65%. The ratio calculation excludes assets, liabilities, revenues, and expenses included in MGE's financial statements as the result of the consolidation of VIEs, such as MGE Power West Campus and MGE Power Elm Road. A change in control constitutes a default under the agreements. Change in control events are defined as (i) a failure by MGE&nbsp;Energy to hold 100% of the outstanding voting equity interest in MGE or (ii) the acquisition of beneficial ownership of 30% or more of the outstanding voting stock of MGE&nbsp;Energy by one person or two or more persons acting in concert. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, MGE was in compliance with the covenant requirements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	c.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_E2D5BD1340944D18BA8EA5AA7852479A">
</A>

</P>

	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_319D99953E8E4CB9976326A63BBB950E">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_F4DDFFF400A841B0874006966B62934B">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:72PX; WIDTH:96PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(a)
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_FS_3E72083A137543FEACF080503BA1FE5A">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:96PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy short-term borrowings include MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE lines of credit and MGE commercial paper.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; WIDTH:36PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	11.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_D8ADE1BD51FF4E298D9E2D57DC2E9E1E">
</A>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Fair Value of Financial Instruments - MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TS_BDF73BABC4344621AD19AF6FCB7BC88E">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX">
	Fair value is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or would be paid to transfer a liability (an exit price) in the principal or most advantageous market for the asset or liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. The accounting standard clarifies that fair value should be based on the assumptions market participants would use when pricing the asset or liability including assumptions about risk. The standard also establishes a three level fair value hierarchy based upon the observability of the assumptions used and requires the use of observable market data when available. The levels are:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Level 1 - Pricing inputs are quoted prices within active markets for identical assets or liabilities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Level 2 - Pricing inputs are quoted prices within active markets for similar assets or liabilities; quoted prices for identical or similar instruments in markets that are not active; and model-derived valuations that are correlated with or otherwise verifiable by observable market data.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	Level 3 - Pricing inputs are unobservable and reflect management's best estimate of what market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>
<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=638.4 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=638.4>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:298PX">
	78
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:9.6PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1.333>
<A NAME="eolPage79"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	a.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Fair Value of Financial Assets and Liabilities Recorded at the Carrying Amount.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_5B32EE75A7374BF188DE3ABC0350A5C1">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, the carrying amount of cash, cash equivalents, and outstanding commercial paper approximates fair market value due to the short maturity of those investments and obligations. The estimated fair market value of MGE&nbsp;Energy's and MGE's long-term debt is based on quoted market prices for similar financial instruments at December&nbsp;31. Since long-term debt is not traded in an active market, it is classified as Level 2.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_8379176C01264716A2715380E727E4AB">
</A>
	The estimated fair market value of financial instruments are as follows:
</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_5489080172A5442797DF4F1FA5DB8E4D">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_4A972552E2B2428A89F796BB15315A4F">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX">
	No transfers were made in or out of Level 1 or Level 2 for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX">
	Investments include exchange-traded investment securities valued using quoted prices on active exchanges and are therefore classified as Level 1.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX">
	Derivatives include exchange-traded derivative contracts, over-the-counter transactions, a purchased power agreement, and FTRs. Most exchange-traded derivative contracts are valued based on unadjusted quoted prices in active markets and are therefore classified as Level 1. A small number of exchange-traded derivative contracts are valued using quoted market pricing in markets with insufficient volumes and are therefore considered unobservable and classified as Level 3. Transactions done with an over-the-counter party are on inactive markets and are therefore classified as Level 3. These transactions are valued based on quoted prices from markets with similar exchange-traded transactions. FTRs are priced based upon monthly auction results for identical or similar instruments in a closed market with limited data available and are therefore classified as Level 3.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX">
	The purchased power agreement (see Footnote&nbsp;15) was valued using an internally-developed pricing model and therefore is classified as Level 3. The model projects future market energy prices and compares those prices to the projected power costs to be incurred under the contract. Inputs to the model require significant management judgment and estimation. Future energy prices are based on a forward power pricing curve using exchange-traded contracts in the electric futures market, where such exchange-traded contracts exist, and upon calculations based on forward gas prices, where such exchange-traded contracts do not exist. A basis adjustment is applied to the market energy price to reflect the price differential between the market price delivery point and the counterparty delivery point. The historical relationship between the delivery points is reviewed and a discount (below 100%) or premium (above 100%) is derived. This comparison is done for both peak times when demand is high and off peak times when demand is low. If the basis adjustment is lowered, the fair value measurement will decrease, and if the basis adjustment is increased, the fair value measurement will increase.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX">
	The projected power costs anticipated to be incurred under the purchased power agreement are determined using many factors, including historical generating costs, future prices, and expected fuel mix of the counterparty. An increase in the projected fuel costs would result in a decrease in the fair value measurement of the purchased power agreement. A significant input that MGE estimates is the counterparty's fuel mix in determining the projected power cost. MGE also considers the assumptions that market participants would use in valuing the asset or liability. This consideration includes assumptions about market risk such as liquidity, volatility, and contract duration. The fair value model uses a discount rate that incorporates discounting, credit, and model risks.
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_ED7398CE5A8B48DAAFD513D27B595905">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
</DIV>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TAG21">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_04E6D264587648ADB357476B529CD5E1">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_TAG320">
</A>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_DDD3F05A57DC4CD885AF399B4221A293">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX">
	The deferred compensation plan allows participants to defer certain cash compensation into a notional investment account. These amounts are included within other deferred liabilities in the consolidated balance sheets of MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE. The notional investments earn interest based upon the semiannual rate of U.S. Treasury Bills having a 26 week maturity increased by 1% compounded monthly with a minimum annual rate of 7%, compounded monthly. The notional investments are based upon observable market data, however since the deferred compensation obligations themselves are not exchanged in an active market they are classified as Level 2.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_A69496D5CC8B429BB0C85B84149D1597">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60.467PX">
	The following table summarizes the changes in Level 3 assets and liabilities measured at fair value on a recurring basis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>

	MGE's exchange-traded derivative contracts, over-the-counter party transactions, purchased power agreement, and FTRs are subject to regulatory deferral. These derivatives are therefore marked to fair value and are offset in the financial statements with a corresponding regulatory asset or liability.

	12.
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_4663235957434C1AA9A035439256882A">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:36PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	Income Taxes.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:36PX; WIDTH:60PX; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	a.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX">
<B>
	MGE&nbsp;Energy and MGE Income Taxes.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	MGE&nbsp;Energy files a consolidated federal income tax return that includes the operations of all subsidiary companies. The subsidiaries calculate their respective federal income tax provisions as if they were separate taxable entities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="F10K_2016_HTM_XBRL_CS_032C8B946F0D47169E4695177C9DDAAE">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:60PX">
	On a consolidated and separate company basis, the income tax provision consists of the following provision (benefit) components for the years ended December&nbsp;31:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
